{{Politics of the Central African Republic}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in the [[Central African Republic]] on 13 and 14 December 2015.<ref name=R>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-centralafrica-referendum-idUKKBN0TX1T620151214 Voting extended for Central African referendum after violence] Reuters, 14 December 2015</ref> The referendum was originally scheduled to be held on 5 October 2015, prior to general elections,<ref name=ENCA>[https://www.enca.com/africa/central-african-republic-council-adopts-new-constitution Central African Republic council adopts new constitution] ENCA, 1 September 2015</ref> but was later delayed. Violence on polling day led to voting being extended for another day.<ref name=R/> The new constitution was approved by 93% of voters.<ref>[http://www.dw.com/en/central-african-republic-voters-say-yes-to-new-constitution/a-18933653 Central African Republic voters say yes to new constitution] Deutsche Welle, 22 December 2015</ref> [[Central African general election, 2015–16|General elections]] followed on 30 December.
==Background== {{see|Central African Republic Civil War (2012–present)}} The new constitution was approved by a large majority in the Transitional Council on 30 August 2015.<ref name=ENCA/> It provides for the creation of a Senate and a National Election Authority, as well as requiring decisions made by the President and Prime Minister to be approved by ministers, and for the government to inform the National Assembly when a contract relating to mineral resources is signed.<ref name=ENCA/> Only 15,000 copies of the new constitution were published.
==Conduct== An unidentified [[MINUSCA]] source said that voting was delayed in several districts across [[Bangui]], although not in the PK5 district, where gunfire broke out overnight. Approximately two million citizens registered to vote. Many of the 5,600 polling stations were located in remote regions.<Ref>[http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2015/12/13/441548/Central-African-Republic-Bangui-Referendum-Constitution- Constitutional referendum begins in violence-wracked CAR] Press TV, 13 December 2015</ref>
