{{about|ancient copyists|the insect|Ips calligraphus}}

A '''calligraphus''' (pl. ''calligraphi'') was an ancient [[copyist]] or [[scrivener]], who transcribed correctly and in its entirety what the [[Notary public|notaries]] had taken down in notes, or minutes—duties similar to the modern work of engrossing.

The minutes of acts, etc., were always taken down in a kind of [[cipher]], or [[shorthand]], so that the ''Notaries'', as the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] called them, or the ''{{lang|grc|Σημειόγραφοι}}'' and ''{{lang|grc|Ταχύγραφοι}}'', as the [[Ancient Greeks|Greeks]] called them, could keep pace with a speaker or person who dictated. These notes being understood by few, were copied exactly by people with good handwriting; these were called ''calligraphi'', a name often found in ancient writings.

